            <abstract>
                <p>This astrological text contains descriptions of the twelve zodiac signs, including their position in the sky, appearance, astrological characteristics, and corresponding periods. 
                    Each description of a zodiac sign concludes with a separate section on women. According to <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/ACFXC8CA"><seg type="book"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Neugebauer1979Astronomy"/><title level="m">Ethiopic Astronomy and Computus</title><title level="s">Österreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften, philosophisch-historische Klasse, Sitzungsberichte</title><author><forename>Otto</forename><surname>Neugebauer</surname></author><pubPlace>Wien</pubPlace><publisher>Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften</publisher><date>1979</date><series><title level="s">Österreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften, philosophisch-historische Klasse, Sitzungsberichte</title><biblScope unit="volume">347, Veröffentlichungen der Kommission für Geschichte der Mathematik, Naturwissenschaften und Medizin, 22</biblScope></series><biblScope unit="volume">347, Veröffentlichungen der Kommission für Geschichte der Mathematik, Naturwissenschaften und Medizin, 22</biblScope><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:Neugebauer1979Astronomy</note></note><note type="tag">bm:Neugebauer1979Astronomy</note><citedRange unit="page">162</citedRange></bibl>, the mathematical operation required for identification of a corresponding zodiac sign is a reduction modulo 12 of the numerical equivalents of a person's name 
                    and the name of the mother, that is a divisian by 12 with a remainder. The remainder is the parameter which defines the corresponding zodiacal sign.
                    The text demonstrates a fairly stable structure, but there is some variability in wording across different manuscripts. All zodiac names are transliterated from Arabic. In <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/EMIP02288">Portland, Ethiopic Manuscript Imaging Project, Weiner Codex 282</ref>, 
                    the text contains a short, almost illegible, note on the purpose and possibly the authorship of the text.</p>
            </abstract>
